Picking rules (hard preferences, in order):
1. **GitHub: issue / PR / commit / security advisory > bare repo root.** If both `github.com/org/repo` and `github.com/org/repo/issues/N` appear, pick the issue. Same for commits and PRs.
2. **Bug tracker entries** (bugzilla.*, bugs.debian.org, bugs.gentoo.org, bugs.launchpad.net) — they carry the original technical discussion.
3. **Vendor security advisories** with CVE-specific pages (access.redhat.com/security/cve/..., security.*, *.vendor.com/security/...) when they link directly to this CVE.
4. **Writeups** that describe the vulnerable code path, CVSS vector derivation, or an exploit sketch.

Hard exclusions (never pick):
- `vuldb.com` — login-walled.
- `cvedetails.com`, `cve.mitre.org` — aggregators, nothing beyond NVD.
- `nvd.nist.gov` — we are already reading it.
- Press / media: arstechnica.com, bleepingcomputer.com, theregister.com, wired.com, bloomberg.com, ft.com, therecord.media, darkreading.com, securityweek.com. Narrative, not technical.
- Release notes pages with no CVE-specific content.
- Broken / dead links flagged as such.

